headline: A criticized Airbnb deal will let users play gladiator in Rome's Colosseum
summary: The ancient Roman Colosseum will be the venue of gladiator fights — albeit staged — for the first time in two millennia under a $1.5 million sponsorship deal with Airbnb that aims to promote “a more conscious tourism.”  Under the deal announced by Airbnb and the Colosseum on Wednesday, the sponsorship by the short-term rental giant will cover the renewal of an educational program inside the ancient Roman amphitheater covering the history of the structure and gladiators.  Eight of the platform's users and their plus-ones will be able to participate in faux gladiator fights after the Colosseum's closing time on May 7-8, taking the same underground route used by gladiators in ancient Rome to reach the arena.

An environment in which market participants expect a growing economy and a broad-based rise in corporate earnings favors companies whose sales are relatively sensitive to changes in economic demand, so their profits jump when the economy strengthens.
